00:00:38.090 --> 00:00:39.064
are not yours.

00:00:39.064 --> 00:00:40.980
And then I'll talk a
little bit about hosting.

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:42.480
And then if we have time--
I don't know if we will--

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:44.850
at the end, we'll do a little
bit of hosting practice.

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:46.470
But part of the
hosting practice will

00:00:46.470 --> 00:00:47.761
come with the writing practice.

00:00:47.761 --> 00:00:50.220
It's hard to separate them.

00:00:50.220 --> 00:00:53.630
I'm going to talk for like
maybe 10 minutes about writing.

00:00:53.630 --> 00:00:56.210
And then we'll just get
right into the practice.

00:00:56.210 --> 00:00:59.800
I'm going to overload you with
a bunch of guidelines or rules

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:01.517
or however you want
to think about it.

00:01:01.517 --> 00:01:03.850
Don't worry about remembering
them or writing them down.

00:01:03.850 --> 00:01:05.379
But we'll come
back to them all as

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:07.712
we do the practice, because
that's really how you learn,

00:01:07.712 --> 00:01:10.080
is by doing.

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:12.480
This is one way to write.

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:16.020
It's kind of how I
approach writing.

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:17.010
You start with an idea.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:20.120
You're like, hey, it'd be great
have a video about whatever, x.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:22.969
And then the explosion
phase is the,

00:01:22.969 --> 00:01:25.260
I'm going to think about
everything that could possibly

00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:26.379
relate to this idea.

00:01:26.379 --> 00:01:27.670
I'm going to write it all down.

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:30.180
I think you saw an example
of that with Elizabeth's snot

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:30.900
brainstorm.

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:33.180
Brainstorm is
another word for it.

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:35.170
And then from there,
you sort of go outward

00:01:35.170 --> 00:01:37.030
and then you distill
it down to the essence,

00:01:37.030 --> 00:01:42.040
like what is the actual point of
the video, who, what, how, why.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:44.249
Where is sometimes
important, but not usually.

00:01:44.249 --> 00:01:46.790
And then the stuff that we're
going to talk about today, this

00:01:46.790 --> 00:01:49.810
is the writing piece of it.

00:01:49.810 --> 00:01:53.030
So when you write
a script, you want

00:01:53.030 --> 00:01:55.550
to pay attention to structure.

00:01:55.550 --> 00:01:57.225
So what do you talk about first?

00:01:57.225 --> 00:01:58.100
What's in the middle?

00:01:58.100 --> 00:01:58.850
How do you end it?

00:01:58.850 --> 00:01:59.790
That kind of thing.

00:01:59.790 --> 00:02:01.570
Tone-- are you going for funny?

00:02:01.570 --> 00:02:02.770
Are you going for dry?

00:02:02.770 --> 00:02:05.350
Are you going for informal?

00:02:05.350 --> 00:02:07.810
Are you going for formal?

00:02:07.810 --> 00:02:10.909
Jargon-- you want to
generally try to avoid jargon,

00:02:10.909 --> 00:02:13.450
especially if you're shooting
for high school, middle school,

00:02:13.450 --> 00:02:16.260
that range.

00:02:16.260 --> 00:02:19.940
By the way, it's ironic that
I'm using the word jargon.

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:23.252
Jargon is a technical language,
which jargon is itself

00:02:23.252 --> 00:02:23.960
a technical word.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:26.860
So that's sort of an
ironic thing there.

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:29.500
Visuals-- you always want to
write the script, because video

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:30.647
is a weird medium.

00:02:30.647 --> 00:02:32.230
I mean, you've got
the image, and then

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:33.740
you've got the
soundtrack, and you

00:02:33.740 --> 00:02:36.870
want to make sure
that they are related

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:39.230
and don't duplicate each other.

00:02:39.230 --> 00:02:42.430
So that is a trick
that we'll get into.

00:02:42.430 --> 00:02:43.950
I was reading some
of your examples

00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:47.682
and there are particular
sentences where this is

00:02:47.682 --> 00:02:48.890
going to be really important.

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:53.220
So if I don't talk about
that on my own, remind me.

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:58.050
Metaphors and jokes-- it's
really hard to be funny.

00:02:58.050 --> 00:03:00.496
So if you think you can,
and you want to try,

00:03:00.496 --> 00:03:01.620
then I would say go for it.

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:04.830
But generally, I
try to avoid jokes.

00:03:04.830 --> 00:03:06.370
Metaphors are
similar, it's kind of

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:07.330
hard to write a good metaphor.

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:08.863
Do we all know what a
metaphor is, by the way?

00:03:08.863 --> 00:03:11.238
PROFESSOR: I showed them the
[INAUDIBLE] video yesterday.

00:03:11.238 --> 00:03:13.760
GEORGE ZAIDAN: OK, cool.

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:16.900
So those are sort of-- the stuff
on the left is in every video,

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:17.570
you've got to pay attention to.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:19.040
The stuff on the right, the
metaphors and the jokes,

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:20.210
are sort of advanced.

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:23.710
Anyway, then once you sort of
get your first draft together,

00:03:23.710 --> 00:03:25.710
you explode, you distill
that into your essence,

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:28.612
then you condense it, and
you write your script.

00:03:28.612 --> 00:03:29.820
And this doesn't happen once.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:31.180
This happens many, many times.

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:35.400
Typically, a script will
go through between 4

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:38.460
and like 12 revisions before
we actually shoot it, up to

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:42.252
and including-- we're rewriting
five minutes before we shoot.

00:03:42.252 --> 00:03:44.210
Because you say it out
loud, and something just

00:03:44.210 --> 00:03:46.200
doesn't sound
right, and you feel

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:48.090
like you have to change it.

00:03:48.090 --> 00:03:51.540
So this is generally how
my writing process works.

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:53.360
Other people do it
completely differently.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:54.600
This is sort of an MIT approach.

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:56.260
It's very sort of
structured and logical,

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:57.680
but it doesn't have
to be this way.

00:03:57.680 --> 00:03:59.221
If you don't want
to write like this,

00:03:59.221 --> 00:04:01.960
you absolutely don't have to.

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:05.750
The first writing guideline,
this is in addition to the flow

00:04:05.750 --> 00:04:07.700
chart, is-- and I
think you guys talked

00:04:07.700 --> 00:04:10.610
about this a little bit
already-- know your audience

00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:11.910
and write for them.

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:15.024
And I have this note down
there, not necessarily to them.

00:04:15.024 --> 00:04:17.399
So most of the videos that
you're going to be working for

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:20.589
are aimed at people
younger than you than you,

00:04:20.589 --> 00:04:23.340
and sometimes people a
lot younger than you.

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:27.260
I mean, maybe even down to like
6th, 7th grade, middle school.

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:30.910
So you want to write to
their level of education,

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:34.370
but not necessarily
talk as if you were

00:04:34.370 --> 00:04:37.130
talking to a middle schooler.

00:04:37.130 --> 00:04:39.608
Does anyone know what I
mean by that distinction?

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:47.740
I'll cold call if
people don't speak up.

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:49.230
AUDIENCE: Like, don't baby talk?

00:04:49.230 --> 00:04:50.188
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Exactly.

00:04:50.188 --> 00:04:50.810
Yeah, exactly.

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:51.590
Don't baby talk.

00:04:51.590 --> 00:04:56.190
So give me an example of like--
pick a sentence, any sentence.

00:04:56.190 --> 00:04:58.410
You can read it off the
intellectual property form

00:04:58.410 --> 00:04:59.576
in front of you if you want.

00:04:59.576 --> 00:05:02.664
But give me the non--
just the regular version.

00:05:02.664 --> 00:05:04.080
And give me the
baby talk version,

00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:05.080
just so we have a sense.

00:05:11.855 --> 00:05:12.730
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:27.044 --> 00:05:28.710
GEORGE ZAIDAN: No,
that's exactly right.

00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:30.960
And you guys notice that
it's funny when he does that.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:33.260
There's just
something ridiculous

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:36.829
about-- you call it baby talk
or talking down to your audience

00:05:36.829 --> 00:05:39.120
or something-- that you
immediately don't pay attention

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:40.280
to what he's saying.

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:41.960
You pay attention to
how he's saying it.

00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:43.900
And you've lost your
audience immediately.

00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:46.460
So that's a really
important distinction.

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:48.210
By the way, this holds
true if you're just

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:50.760
interacting with kids anyway.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.080
Most kids are smarter than
we give them credit for.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:57.720
And people baby talk
kids all the time.

00:05:57.720 --> 00:05:59.510
But if you just
straight talk to them,

00:05:59.510 --> 00:06:01.926
you'll be surprised at the
kind of responses that you get.

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:05.900
Rule number two--
or guideline, sorry,

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:07.880
number two-- is write it
like you would say it,

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:09.430
because you will be saying it.

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:14.170
What I mean here is
your script is a draft.

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:15.832
And it will always be a draft.

00:06:15.832 --> 00:06:17.290
You will never have
a final script,

00:06:17.290 --> 00:06:19.800
because nobody's going
to log on to the internet

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:20.770
and read your scripts.

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:23.300
What they're going to do is
hear you say the words that

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:24.440
are on your script.

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:27.274
So even if a sentence
is great on paper

00:06:27.274 --> 00:06:29.440
and you read it in your
head and it sounds awesome--

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:31.520
if when you say it out
loud it, it sounds weird

00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:33.960
or it's hard to
understand or whatever,

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:36.140
then it doesn't matter how
great it looked on paper.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:38.917
It's not an effective sentence.

00:06:38.917 --> 00:06:41.250
This is the most important
thing we'll talk about today.

00:06:41.250 --> 00:06:45.250
We'll come back to that
when we do the practice.

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:48.150
This is another version
of the previous slide.

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:50.940
When you-- and you
guys are all know this

00:06:50.940 --> 00:06:52.830
because you read
scientific journal articles

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:57.290
and stuff-- when you read that
kind of text, it's very dense.

00:06:57.290 --> 00:07:00.680
It's extremely well structured
and logically laid out.

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:02.010
It has a lot of jargon.

00:07:02.010 --> 00:07:03.930
It's very precise.

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:05.870
There's very little ambiguity.

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:07.890
And it's understated,
and it's elegant.

00:07:07.890 --> 00:07:14.130
Meaning like-- usually people
take the fewest possible words

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:18.630
to say something, and that means
using long and complex words.

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:20.330
And it is beautiful to read.

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:21.762
It's great English.

00:07:21.762 --> 00:07:24.220
But if you try and read it out
loud and you do it on video,

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:26.100
again, you'll lose your
audience instantly.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:28.530
It's just as bad as baby talk.

00:07:28.530 --> 00:07:33.156
When you talk-- people talk
in-- people are very repetitive.

00:07:33.156 --> 00:07:33.780
They say, "uh."

00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:34.640
They say, "um."

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:37.020
They-- uh-- like I just did.

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:40.220
They don't really
use fancy words.

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:43.480
If their audience
doesn't understand,

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:46.120
they stop and they
try another approach.

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:48.590
It's a lot more free-form,
a lot more inconsistent,

00:07:48.590 --> 00:07:49.790
a lot fluffier.

00:07:49.790 --> 00:07:52.000
And that's what you
want to shoot for,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.940
because you will be on
screen talking to the camera

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:56.990
as if that camera
is another person.

00:07:56.990 --> 00:08:00.079
And so that's the write
it like you say it.

00:08:00.079 --> 00:08:02.620
That's what I mean when I say
write it like you would say it.

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:09.599
Another-- and I think this
is the last guideline-- is

00:08:09.599 --> 00:08:10.890
you really want to be accurate.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:11.740
Because, obviously,
you don't want

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:13.610
to say things that are
wrong in your videos.

00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:16.050
But accuracy is not the
same thing as detail.

00:08:16.050 --> 00:08:19.330
So this is the difference
between going back

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:20.160
to the last slide.

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:25.510
Being very, very,
very precise usually

00:08:25.510 --> 00:08:26.600
requires a lot of detail.

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:29.480
If you want to say
exactly what you mean,

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:32.169
it probably will take you a
couple sentences to say it.

00:08:32.169 --> 00:08:35.432
But if you want to
be accurate, that

00:08:35.432 --> 00:08:36.890
is going to-- and
especially if you

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:38.330
want to be accurate
for a short five minute

00:08:38.330 --> 00:08:40.590
video-- that's going to mean
leaving information out.

00:08:40.590 --> 00:08:42.669
And that's OK.

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:47.240
The test that I like
to subject scripts to

00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:51.090
is, can an eighth
grader understand it?

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:52.140
If so, great.

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:56.010
And can a PhD In the subject
matter of that script

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:56.860
read the script.

00:08:56.860 --> 00:09:00.540
And if their reaction is, wow,
this is surprisingly accurate,

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:03.650
then you've done a good job.

00:09:03.650 --> 00:09:06.130
And that's all.

00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:07.550
That's it for my rules.

00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:10.270
Hopefully that was
less than 10 minutes.

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:14.760
What I want to do now is put
these rules in to practice.

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:20.730
We're going to start with a
quote that is not one of yours.

00:09:20.730 --> 00:09:23.640
And then we'll move
into your scripts.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:25.610
So I'm going to go ahead
and-- let me pick one.

00:09:33.730 --> 00:09:36.141
Let's do the first one.

00:09:36.141 --> 00:09:36.640
OK.

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:39.910
So let's see.

00:09:39.910 --> 00:09:41.744
Everyone take a second
and just read this.

00:09:54.831 --> 00:09:56.080
So you'll notice the citation.

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:57.480
This is from a paper.

00:09:57.480 --> 00:09:59.690
It's written English.

00:09:59.690 --> 00:10:02.740
Can someone just shout
out some of the rules

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:07.420
that would make this bad for
speaking and reading aloud?

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:10.060
In fact, why don't we-- let's
actually read this aloud just

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:11.180
to see how it sounds.

00:10:11.180 --> 00:10:14.880
So anthropogenic CO2
emissions are contributing

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:16.820
to global climate change
and could negatively

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:19.990
impact our way of life if
serious action is further

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:22.220
delayed.

00:10:22.220 --> 00:10:22.720
OK.

00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:24.880
So what rules are
we breaking, or what

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:26.005
guidelines are we breaking?

00:10:29.959 --> 00:10:31.750
AUDIENCE: I think just
hearing it out loud,

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:34.940
it seems kind of-- life if you
were presenting it to someone,

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:35.980
it'd be a long sentence.

00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:38.180
And it's very statement.

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:39.540
It's not conversational.

00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:43.420
It's not like you're-- you know,
it's not written like you would

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:43.920
speak.

00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:45.890
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Exactly.

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:47.282
What else?

00:10:47.282 --> 00:10:49.602
AUDIENCE: The word
anthropogenic is

00:10:49.602 --> 00:10:51.402
difficult to hear and remember.

00:10:51.402 --> 00:10:52.360
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Exactly.

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:53.800
It's also jargon.

00:10:53.800 --> 00:10:56.090
It means human-made.

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:57.930
AUDIENCE: It's a very
passive sentence.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:10:59.200
GEORGE ZAIDAN: It
is a very passive--

00:10:59.200 --> 00:10:59.780
what you mean by that?

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:00.477
Explain.

00:11:00.477 --> 00:11:02.310
AUDIENCE: Well, if
further delayed-- I mean,

00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:04.945
what you really mean is
this could be troublesome.

00:11:04.945 --> 00:11:05.515
This is bad.

00:11:05.515 --> 00:11:06.015
Right?

00:11:06.015 --> 00:11:07.010
Or it could be bad.

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:07.510
Right?

00:11:07.510 --> 00:11:09.301
But their way of stating
as further delayed

00:11:09.301 --> 00:11:12.510
isn't very-- it's
not a very active way

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:14.925
of saying the same thing.

00:11:14.925 --> 00:11:17.050
GEORGE ZAIDAN: So here's
another interesting thing.

00:11:17.050 --> 00:11:20.155
Negatively impact-- those
are not difficult words.

00:11:20.155 --> 00:11:21.780
It's easy to understand
what they mean,

00:11:21.780 --> 00:11:24.050
but let's think about
that for a second.

00:11:24.050 --> 00:11:27.760
So what doesn't negatively
impact our way of life

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.209
mean in colloquial language?

00:11:29.209 --> 00:11:31.500
What would you say to someone
if you were going to say,

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:35.554
in 100 years climate
change will do what?

00:11:35.554 --> 00:11:36.480
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:37.110
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Yeah.

00:11:37.110 --> 00:11:38.730
Will it negatively
impact our way of life?

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:39.980
No, it's going to kill us all.

00:11:39.980 --> 00:11:45.290
That's sort of the real-life
subtext of this sentence.

00:11:45.290 --> 00:11:46.228
What else?

00:11:54.196 --> 00:11:56.188
AUDIENCE: The are a lot
of complicated grammar

00:11:56.188 --> 00:11:59.040
structures-- are
contributed, is delayed.

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:00.740
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Mm-hmm.

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:03.940
You have to-- I mean, you wait
till the end of the sentence

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:05.250
before you get the payoff.

00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:06.120
Right?

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:08.900
You don't understand what
the point of the sentence

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:12.527
is until you get to "negatively
impact our way of life

00:12:12.527 --> 00:12:14.110
if serious action
is further delayed."

00:12:14.110 --> 00:12:15.859
And really, you don't
understand-- I mean,

00:12:15.859 --> 00:12:17.310
the point is we need to act now.

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:18.810
That's what this
sentence is saying.

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:21.000
If we act later, we're screwed.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.510
And you don't get that until,
"if serious action is further

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:24.010
delayed."

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:26.814
So yeah, the payoff really
comes at the very, very end.

00:12:26.814 --> 00:12:30.246
AUDIENCE: It's a fun exercise to
eliminate all of the adjectives

00:12:30.246 --> 00:12:33.260
and look at the nouns and verbs.

00:12:33.260 --> 00:12:33.860
Right?

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:35.776
Just take a second and
see if you can do that.

00:12:35.776 --> 00:12:38.690
It actually makes
it really simple.

00:12:38.690 --> 00:12:49.780
Emissions are contributing
to change and impact--

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:52.467
like picking out all of the
things that suddenly simplifies

00:12:52.467 --> 00:12:54.915
everything-- [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:54.915 --> 00:12:56.456
There's a lot of
descriptors in there

00:12:56.456 --> 00:12:58.600
that are very distracting.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:01.750
So now that we've
done this, let's

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:05.352
rephrase it as if we were
saying it to someone on camera.

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:10.762
PROFESSOR: Or what if just
to someone in general?

00:13:10.762 --> 00:13:12.720
GEORGE ZAIDAN: OK, yeah,
to someone in general.

00:13:12.720 --> 00:13:15.640
Say it to me.

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:16.532
Anyone.

00:13:16.532 --> 00:13:21.396
AUDIENCE: If we don't
act now, [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:21.396 --> 00:13:22.270
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Right.

00:13:22.270 --> 00:13:24.815
Another version.

00:13:24.815 --> 00:13:28.285
AUDIENCE: Man-made CO2
emissions are hurting us.

00:13:28.285 --> 00:13:29.255
GEORGE ZAIDAN: OK.

00:13:29.255 --> 00:13:31.195
Another.

00:13:31.195 --> 00:13:32.650
Yeah.

00:13:32.650 --> 00:13:34.470
AUDIENCE: Humans
create CO2 emissions.

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:38.220
We must act now or suffer.

00:13:38.220 --> 00:13:39.360
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I like that.

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:40.900
We must act now or suffer.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:41.790
That's good.

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:42.626
Anyone else?

00:13:50.393 --> 00:13:51.934
Someone who hasn't
said anything yet.

00:14:08.895 --> 00:14:12.110
AUDIENCE: If we don't
stop emitting CO2,

00:14:12.110 --> 00:14:15.027
life will look very
different soon.

00:14:15.027 --> 00:14:15.860
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Good.

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:16.359
OK.

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:23.340
So the point I'm trying to make
by having five or six of you

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:26.040
say it each a different way
is that there is no one right

00:14:26.040 --> 00:14:28.410
way to write a script.

00:14:28.410 --> 00:14:32.450
There are lots of interesting,
engaging, dramatic ways

00:14:32.450 --> 00:14:34.180
to say the same thing.

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:35.770
And we are going to
get into that now

00:14:35.770 --> 00:14:38.350
with your examples, which
we're going to spend

00:14:38.350 --> 00:14:41.885
considerably more time on.

00:14:41.885 --> 00:14:43.497
PROFESSOR: Before
you move on, George.

00:14:43.497 --> 00:14:44.288
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Yes?

00:14:44.288 --> 00:14:48.920
PROFESSOR: So it's always an
Interesting challenge balancing

00:14:48.920 --> 00:14:52.974
avoiding being too
jargon-y and ending up

00:14:52.974 --> 00:14:53.890
baiting your audience.

00:14:53.890 --> 00:14:54.070
Right?

00:14:54.070 --> 00:14:56.660
Like, there's no reason why you
can't say that words, climate

00:14:56.660 --> 00:14:57.912
change.

00:14:57.912 --> 00:15:02.421
Even though those are technical
terms. [INAUDIBLE] What was it?

00:15:02.421 --> 00:15:02.920
Anthro--

00:15:02.920 --> 00:15:03.420
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Anthropogenic.

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:04.920
PROFESSOR: Anthropogenic.

00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:07.130
I mean, we talk about this
with [INAUDIBLE] scripts

00:15:07.130 --> 00:15:07.730
all the time.

00:15:07.730 --> 00:15:11.764
The way you deliver
a word, for instance,

00:15:11.764 --> 00:15:14.252
can help a lot with conveying.

00:15:14.252 --> 00:15:15.845
What was the word-- [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:15.845 --> 00:15:17.220
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I
mean if you want

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:20.687
to-- if you're going to use that
same word four or five times

00:15:20.687 --> 00:15:22.770
throughout the script, and
it's an important word,

00:15:22.770 --> 00:15:25.180
and it relates to a
demo or something--

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:27.580
if there's some reason
for you to use jargon,

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:28.860
it's OK to define it.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:31.170
As long as you just
define it like you

00:15:31.170 --> 00:15:32.880
would to another person.

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:37.256
Like you say anthropogenic
means human-made.

00:15:37.256 --> 00:15:38.880
And then you go on
and use it later on.

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:39.690
That's fine.

00:15:39.690 --> 00:15:41.450
You don't want to do that
like six times in the video

00:15:41.450 --> 00:15:42.820
and define six different
words, because then you

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:43.660
overload your audience.

00:15:43.660 --> 00:15:44.430
But that's true.

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:46.500
There is-- if you
find yourself having

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:49.150
to say human-made,
man-made, woman-made.

00:15:49.150 --> 00:15:53.190
Like if you are stretching
to try and find alternatives

00:15:53.190 --> 00:15:57.150
to word five or six times that
you could just define and get

00:15:57.150 --> 00:15:58.870
it over with, that's fine.

00:15:58.870 --> 00:16:01.570
I wouldn't limit that
probably to like one or two

00:16:01.570 --> 00:16:04.020
words a video, or
one or two words

00:16:04.020 --> 00:16:05.835
per like three,
four minute video.

00:16:05.835 --> 00:16:08.210
PROFESSOR: And the other reason
why it's really important

00:16:08.210 --> 00:16:11.826
to actually do the exercise of
reading your script out lout,

00:16:11.826 --> 00:16:14.909
or even just flipping
your script over and not

00:16:14.909 --> 00:16:16.950
looking at it and trying
to describe the contents

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:20.136
to the person next to you,
is that-- a very bad habit

00:16:20.136 --> 00:16:22.945
of mine, which I am
constantly finding

00:16:22.945 --> 00:16:25.310
I am annoyed toward
it a lot-- is

00:16:25.310 --> 00:16:27.660
that I get very newscaster-y.

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:31.610
So I may end up having a
script that sounds good

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:33.120
when you say it out loud.

00:16:33.120 --> 00:16:36.320
But it sounds like
you're a reporter talking

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:39.250
about the latest news
update [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:39.250 --> 00:16:42.128
CO2 emission-- can you
go back to that quote?

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:47.470
Yeah, like the middle
part isn't actually

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:49.630
that crazy to say out loud.

00:16:49.630 --> 00:16:51.605
It's contributing to
global climate change

00:16:51.605 --> 00:16:53.910
and could negatively
impact our way of life.

00:16:53.910 --> 00:16:54.410
Right?

00:16:54.410 --> 00:16:57.370
Like that doesn't sound
too crazy to say out loud.

00:16:57.370 --> 00:17:02.030
But it sounds like someone is
saying that in the context of,

00:17:02.030 --> 00:17:05.069
I'm here at the
MIT Course One lab

00:17:05.069 --> 00:17:06.990
where researchers
are finding a way

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:09.759
to prevent global climate
change from negatively impacting

00:17:09.759 --> 00:17:10.349
our life.

00:17:10.349 --> 00:17:10.849
Right?

00:17:10.849 --> 00:17:13.480
It doesn't sound
like I'm just talking

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:18.650
[INAUDIBLE] like a lot of
men in admissions are harming

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:20.460
[INAUDIBLE] life or
something like that.

00:17:20.460 --> 00:17:22.060
I also-- [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:22.060 --> 00:17:23.190
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Yeah.

00:17:23.190 --> 00:17:25.504
The way you write
influences the way

00:17:25.504 --> 00:17:27.170
you're going to
naturally say something.

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:28.919
And you could say this
sentence both ways.

00:17:28.919 --> 00:17:31.530
So you could say it, you know,
anthropogenic CO2 emissions

00:17:31.530 --> 00:17:33.400
are contributing to
global climate change

00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:35.970
and could negatively
impact our way of life

00:17:35.970 --> 00:17:37.890
if serious action
is further delayed.

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:39.860
That sounds like the
7 o'clock news, right?

00:17:39.860 --> 00:17:42.670
You could say you
could say it like this.

00:17:42.670 --> 00:17:44.590
Look, anthropogenic
CO2 emissions

00:17:44.590 --> 00:17:46.391
are contributing to
global climate change.

00:17:46.391 --> 00:17:48.390
And that could really
negatively impact our life

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:49.860
if we don't do
something right now.

00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:51.660
I mean, it's basically
the same line,

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:54.110
but it's said two
completely different ways.

00:17:54.110 --> 00:17:59.790
And it's much harder to say
a line like this naturally,

00:17:59.790 --> 00:18:01.140
but it's possible.

00:18:01.140 --> 00:18:03.960
So the way you
write can impact how

00:18:03.960 --> 00:18:05.240
you end up saying something.

00:18:05.240 --> 00:18:06.281
And that's important too.

00:18:06.281 --> 00:18:09.010
We will-- whoever of
you ends up shooting

00:18:09.010 --> 00:18:10.510
with us in the last
week of January,

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:13.310
we are going to guaranteed
say, no, try that again.

00:18:13.310 --> 00:18:15.840
It sounds too new newscaster-y.

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:18.720
And this is a style choice,
but for Science Out Loud, it's

00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:19.380
not news.

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:21.870
We don't want it to come
across like, here at MIT,

00:18:21.870 --> 00:18:23.370
we're talking to
you about whatever.

00:18:23.370 --> 00:18:24.953
Because MIT already
has a news office.

00:18:24.953 --> 00:18:27.130
They do that well.

00:18:27.130 --> 00:18:28.420
Our goal is different.

00:18:28.420 --> 00:18:33.370
And so making that style choice
consciously from the beginning

00:18:33.370 --> 00:18:34.787
is important.

00:18:34.787 --> 00:18:36.620
But if you want to write
like a newscaster--

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:38.370
I mean, if you're
writing for a news show,

00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:40.420
if the point of
the show is news,

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:44.141
then that could
be perfectly fine.

00:18:44.141 --> 00:18:44.640
Good?

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:46.848
PROFESSOR: Were you going
to show the Ira Glass clip?

00:18:46.848 --> 00:18:47.800
Later for hosting.

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:49.550
Yep.

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:51.930
It might actually be
fine to show that now

00:18:51.930 --> 00:18:53.880
while we're talking about it.

00:18:53.880 --> 00:18:55.814
Let we find it.

00:18:55.814 --> 00:18:56.480
Yep, here we go.

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:01.660
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:02.660
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Oh, yeah.

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:07.635
There we go.

00:19:07.635 --> 00:19:09.275
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:09.275 --> 00:19:11.150
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Do you
guys know who Ira Glass

00:19:11.150 --> 00:19:14.599
is-- This American Life?

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:15.640
He's a radio personality.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:18.660
He's been doing this
for many, many years.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:21.362
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:21.362 --> 00:19:23.320
IRA GLASS: I'm going to
play you a clip of tape

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:25.190
from my eighth year.

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:29.267
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:29.267 --> 00:19:31.350
IRA GLASS: [ON RECORDING]
It's not such a long way

00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:34.380
from the local grocery store
to the international debate

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:37.650
over whether sorghum and meat
production are causing corn

00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:40.070
to decline in Latin America.

00:19:40.070 --> 00:19:41.610
There's a general
air of prosperity

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:45.620
here, partly thanks to
Mexican imports of US grains,

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:48.410
which helps boost
our farm economy.

00:19:48.410 --> 00:19:51.530
Mexico is now one of our
biggest grain customers,

00:19:51.530 --> 00:19:54.910
buying a half billion to $1
billion worth every year,

00:19:54.910 --> 00:19:56.950
including corn to
feed its people

00:19:56.950 --> 00:19:58.952
and sorghum to
feed its livestock.

00:19:58.952 --> 00:20:00.160
Like what am I talking about?

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:02.285
Like, I don't even understand--
like, I wrote this.

00:20:02.285 --> 00:20:05.530
I don't even
understand what it is.

00:20:05.530 --> 00:20:08.810
OK, also, like every part
of this is ill conceived.

00:20:08.810 --> 00:20:11.060
OK?

00:20:11.060 --> 00:20:12.396
The writing is horrible.

00:20:12.396 --> 00:20:14.270
You can't even follow
what I'm talking about.

00:20:14.270 --> 00:20:16.894
And then the performance like--
OK, just a little tip if you're

00:20:16.894 --> 00:20:19.260
performing for broadcast,
you don't underline

00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:22.130
every third word for
emphasis, because it

00:20:22.130 --> 00:20:23.795
sounds really unnatural.

00:20:23.795 --> 00:20:26.420
What you want to do is you want
to talk the way people normally

00:20:26.420 --> 00:20:28.920
talk.

00:20:28.920 --> 00:20:31.440
[ON RECORDING] This helps
cut our own trade deficit

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:34.460
and benefits everyone
in the US economy.

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:36.590
But in Mexico, this
policy has lead

00:20:36.590 --> 00:20:40.150
to fewer tortillas for the
poor and unappetizing tortillas

00:20:40.150 --> 00:20:41.190
for everyone else.

00:20:41.190 --> 00:20:43.950
Again, like this is
the most moronic kind

00:20:43.950 --> 00:20:45.620
of like-- it doesn't
mean anything.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:46.350
And it's hard.

00:20:46.350 --> 00:20:47.885
It's actually kind of an
interesting story, which

00:20:47.885 --> 00:20:49.135
I'll say to you in a sentence.

00:20:49.135 --> 00:20:52.220
Which is, because Mexico
produces a lot of stuff

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:54.720
that they ship to the United
States-- tomatoes and all sorts

00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:57.330
of really wonderful
food that we eat here--

00:20:57.330 --> 00:21:00.020
they don't make enough
corn for their own people.

00:21:00.020 --> 00:21:00.890
That's the story.

00:21:00.890 --> 00:21:04.200
So for us to get
really great tomatoes,

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:06.130
or semi-great
tomatoes, year round,

00:21:06.130 --> 00:21:08.360
basically, Mexicans eat worse.

00:21:08.360 --> 00:21:09.200
That's the story.

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:10.380
And it's kind of an
interesting idea.

00:21:10.380 --> 00:21:10.880
Right?

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:12.940
Like that's actually
sort of like a cool idea

00:21:12.940 --> 00:21:15.430
executed in the
worst possible way.

00:21:15.430 --> 00:21:17.100
So he's talking about
two things there.

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:19.805
The first is how
he wrote the story,

00:21:19.805 --> 00:21:21.680
and the second is how
he delivered the story.

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:22.180
Right?

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:25.370
So in the second part of
the clip where he tells you

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:27.349
the point of the story
in like two sentences

00:21:27.349 --> 00:21:29.390
and you can actually
understand what he's saying,

00:21:29.390 --> 00:21:30.450
that's a writing issue.

00:21:30.450 --> 00:21:33.400
And then the point that he
makes about, don't underline

00:21:33.400 --> 00:21:37.470
every third word, once
you hear that-- like,

00:21:37.470 --> 00:21:40.200
if you listen to the local news
or even the national news--

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.324
I mean, once you hear that,
you can't un-hear that.

00:21:42.324 --> 00:21:46.440
It's incredible how
pervasive that tone is.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:48.000
Because it makes
people sound very

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.910
important and official
when they choose

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:53.740
certain words to underline
and deliver correctly.

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:58.420
And, you know, that is something
that is fine for the news,

00:21:58.420 --> 00:21:59.660
because it has a purpose.

00:21:59.660 --> 00:22:03.790
But it's just-- I mean,
I think it's terrible.

00:22:03.790 --> 00:22:05.980
And Ira Glass does too.

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:10.442
If you listen to-- his show
is called This American Life.

00:22:10.442 --> 00:22:12.150
And if you could just
listen to the first

00:22:12.150 --> 00:22:13.750
like three, four
minutes of any show,

00:22:13.750 --> 00:22:17.450
it's a great example
of really good hosting.

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:20.840
Marketplace is another show
that has a similar style

00:22:20.840 --> 00:22:24.380
and feel to it that's
good to listen to.

00:22:24.380 --> 00:22:28.190
And then everything-- I think
eight minutes past the hour

00:22:28.190 --> 00:22:30.510
or something-- NPR--
or every hour--

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:32.880
NPR goes back to their
local news stations.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:36.200
So you can hear the difference
between newscaster-y delivery

00:22:36.200 --> 00:22:38.040
and natural delivery.

00:22:38.040 --> 00:22:39.290
It's a really good exercise.

00:22:39.290 --> 00:22:41.600
Like I say, once you hear
it, you can't un-hear it.

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:47.490
So let's go back to writing.

