00:38:01.052 --> 00:38:02.260
that you haven't worked with.

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:03.130
GEORGE ZAIDAN: You
reminded me of the thing

00:38:03.130 --> 00:38:03.980
that I was going to talk about.

00:38:03.980 --> 00:38:04.479
Thank you.

00:38:04.479 --> 00:38:06.780
That's exactly what I
wanted to talk about.

00:38:06.780 --> 00:38:10.640
Yeah, so this is really
really, really easy

00:38:10.640 --> 00:38:13.200
to forget when you're writing
a script-- is that there's

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:15.860
going to be a whole other
layer of information that

00:38:15.860 --> 00:38:20.190
is available to your audience
in the final product.

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:24.290
So to the extent that you
can, I would absolutely

00:38:24.290 --> 00:38:26.710
encourage use of
visuals that are

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:28.660
complimentary to the script.

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:34.580
So the way that I-- I don't have
the slides for this, but let's

00:38:34.580 --> 00:38:37.950
say that you wanted
to show a synapse.

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:39.470
You guys know what a synapse is?

00:38:39.470 --> 00:38:45.370
The part in your brain
where neurotransmitters go?

00:38:45.370 --> 00:38:59.070
So you've got this,
this, and then-- OK.

00:38:59.070 --> 00:39:00.360
So this is one nerve.

00:39:00.360 --> 00:39:01.440
This is another nerve.

00:39:01.440 --> 00:39:05.440
This is just the space
in between the nerves.

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:09.060
And these dots are
chemicals that this nerve

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:10.710
is transmitting to this nerve.

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:14.320
These sort of like
Poseidon spears

00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:19.010
are receptors for
these chemicals.

00:39:19.010 --> 00:39:22.980
Now the way that I said that--
if you were to write down

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:26.136
what I just said-- these
dots, this nerve, this space,

00:39:26.136 --> 00:39:28.010
but this area is the
space between the nerve,

00:39:28.010 --> 00:39:30.010
you'd have absolutely no
idea what I was talking

00:39:30.010 --> 00:39:32.010
about without the image.

00:39:32.010 --> 00:39:34.312
Whereas if you didn't
have this image,

00:39:34.312 --> 00:39:36.020
and you were just
writing a script trying

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:39.070
to explain what a synapse
is, you would have to say,

00:39:39.070 --> 00:39:42.080
a synapse is the space
between two nerves.

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:48.000
One nerve releases chemicals
that cross that space

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.640
and get captured by
receptors on the other nerve,

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:55.730
and that's how data is
transmitted from one nerve

00:39:55.730 --> 00:39:57.090
to another.

00:39:57.090 --> 00:39:59.930
So if you were writing a script
without the visuals in mind,

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:01.720
you can very easily
fall into the trap

00:40:01.720 --> 00:40:04.350
of doing what I
just did in writing

00:40:04.350 --> 00:40:05.750
a script that stands alone.

00:40:05.750 --> 00:40:08.710
Whereas if you're
thinking images,

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:10.520
it's going to be mostly
like, look at this.

00:40:10.520 --> 00:40:11.230
Check this out.

00:40:11.230 --> 00:40:14.020
This spaghetti shaped
thing, those dots,

00:40:14.020 --> 00:40:15.560
that kind of
language, and that's

00:40:15.560 --> 00:40:20.056
totally OK and even encouraged
when you're doing a video.

00:40:20.056 --> 00:40:21.430
And that's exactly
what you said.

00:40:21.430 --> 00:40:25.550
Another example is to
basically talk in general terms

00:40:25.550 --> 00:40:29.090
and put specific visuals
that compliment the script.

00:40:29.090 --> 00:40:30.430
You were going to say something?

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:32.586
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
