I think the compartmentalization
is one really--

01:11:20.657 --> 01:11:21.740
it could be a short video.

01:11:21.740 --> 01:11:24.050
It doesn't have to be long.

01:11:24.050 --> 01:11:29.090
And then there's this whole
other-- boats, and ship

01:11:29.090 --> 01:11:30.600
building, and how
do these things,

01:11:30.600 --> 01:11:32.100
how do these giant--
because they've

01:11:32.100 --> 01:11:34.490
gotten big enough now
that you can have 2,000

01:11:34.490 --> 01:11:37.057
or 3,000 people on a ship.

01:11:37.057 --> 01:11:38.390
How do these things stay afloat?

01:11:38.390 --> 01:11:40.330
It'd be really cool, I think.

01:11:40.330 --> 01:11:43.110
AUDIENCE: From an educational
context point of view.

01:11:43.110 --> 01:11:45.430
With the K-12 videos program
in its old iteration,

01:11:45.430 --> 01:11:48.300
where people made
their own episodes,

01:11:48.300 --> 01:11:50.800
there were like 10
episodes on buoyancy.

01:11:50.800 --> 01:11:54.350
I don't know why people are so
obsessed with explaining it,

01:11:54.350 --> 01:11:57.270
but I think it's because it's
a topic that maybe people

01:11:57.270 --> 01:11:58.861
struggled with in school.

01:11:58.861 --> 01:12:00.360
AUDIENCE: No, it's
a framework test.

01:12:00.360 --> 01:12:04.550
So, second graders-- it's
the essential question that

01:12:04.550 --> 01:12:05.870
is asked in the curriculum.

01:12:05.870 --> 01:12:06.870
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Buoyancy?

01:12:06.870 --> 01:12:08.078
AUDIENCE: Yes, sink or float.

01:12:08.078 --> 01:12:09.470
What sinks, what
floats, and why?

01:12:09.470 --> 01:12:12.510
And it's a questions
that's intended to get

01:12:12.510 --> 01:12:14.700
them thinking scientifically.

01:12:14.700 --> 01:12:16.990
And so that big
buoyancy question

01:12:16.990 --> 01:12:18.900
is-- when I was learning
to be a teacher,

01:12:18.900 --> 01:12:23.300
that was the core question, even
in schools that had no science

01:12:23.300 --> 01:12:25.910
curriculum whatsoever.

01:12:25.910 --> 01:12:28.341
At that age, that's
when they begin

01:12:28.341 --> 01:12:30.340
asking scientific questions,
and that experiment

01:12:30.340 --> 01:12:32.950
is something you need to
do, no matter where you are.

01:12:32.950 --> 01:12:34.860
You have a small bucket.

01:12:34.860 --> 01:12:36.985
Any kid can do it,
regardless of what class.

01:12:36.985 --> 01:12:38.443
I taught in some
inner city schools

01:12:38.443 --> 01:12:40.680
where there no resources,
but you can still

01:12:40.680 --> 01:12:41.790
do that experiment.

01:12:41.790 --> 01:12:45.290
AUDIENCE: Do they figure
out at that age-- do they

01:12:45.290 --> 01:12:49.324
why a sinkable object like
steel would float, or something?

01:12:49.324 --> 01:12:50.990
AUDIENCE: Well the
idea is that students

01:12:50.990 --> 01:12:54.940
can construct themselves with
themselves by experiment.

01:12:54.940 --> 01:12:57.180
So the teacher, if
it's a great teacher,

01:12:57.180 --> 01:13:00.140
will put a bucket of water
and a whole bunch of objects.

01:13:00.140 --> 01:13:02.450
And encourage
students to eventually

01:13:02.450 --> 01:13:04.770
come up with some truths
themselves about what sinks

01:13:04.770 --> 01:13:08.150
and what floats through
hands-on experimentation.

01:13:08.150 --> 01:13:12.250
And that's sort the crux of the
most early science exploration

01:13:12.250 --> 01:13:16.200
in our curriculum, which is
why there's so much on sink

01:13:16.200 --> 01:13:18.685
and float, and that's why
the kids were all-- they

01:13:18.685 --> 01:13:21.110
all were interested in
that when you talk to them,

01:13:21.110 --> 01:13:22.826
because it was
drilled into them,

01:13:22.826 --> 01:13:25.760
at least in our educational
system, the idea of sinking

01:13:25.760 --> 01:13:32.130
and floating and a very
elementary concept that

01:13:32.130 --> 01:13:33.981
is the beginning of
their scientific roots.

01:13:33.981 --> 01:13:35.730
AUDIENCE: But the
reason why I bring it up

01:13:35.730 --> 01:13:38.770
is that there are 100 videos
on sinking and floating,

01:13:38.770 --> 01:13:41.610
and they're all the
exact same thing.

01:13:41.610 --> 01:13:44.180
And every lesson
on buoyancy-- you

01:13:44.180 --> 01:13:47.520
learn it in more
detail in high school.

01:13:47.520 --> 01:13:49.540
It's still on the same thing.

01:13:49.540 --> 01:13:51.070
And this is
presenting it in a way

01:13:51.070 --> 01:13:52.600
that's very, very different.

01:13:52.600 --> 01:13:54.784
And I hesitated to
bring it up at all,

01:13:54.784 --> 01:13:56.825
because I don't want you
to look at those videos,

01:13:56.825 --> 01:13:58.700
and I don't want you to
look at the standards

01:13:58.700 --> 01:14:01.460
and accidentally
default to that style.

01:14:01.460 --> 01:14:04.630
I think you should totally keep
going the way you're going.

01:14:04.630 --> 01:14:06.820
I only wanted to
bring it up, because I

01:14:06.820 --> 01:14:09.235
think that there is
definitely an appetite for it

01:14:09.235 --> 01:14:10.950
in an educational context.

01:14:10.950 --> 01:14:13.520
I also wanted to
bring up that-- it's

01:14:13.520 --> 01:14:16.250
funny-- I wish we could have
the raw footage from all

01:14:16.250 --> 01:14:20.390
the classes just to [INAUDIBLE],
because when you explain

01:14:20.390 --> 01:14:24.400
the technical components
of the wings and stuff--

01:14:24.400 --> 01:14:26.590
we could've used that footage.

01:14:26.590 --> 01:14:29.240
And it's very different from
when you read this aloud.

01:14:29.240 --> 01:14:31.760
And the script also
doesn't sound like you

01:14:31.760 --> 01:14:34.610
at all, when you talk.

01:14:34.610 --> 01:14:37.450
And it's a very
difficult thing to do.

01:14:37.450 --> 01:14:39.300
I sympathise with
you guys completely.

01:14:39.300 --> 01:14:42.540
It's really hard to
become self-aware

01:14:42.540 --> 01:14:44.730
of your natural talking style.

01:14:44.730 --> 01:14:48.010
And so some of it
will be just-- maybe

01:14:48.010 --> 01:14:49.760
you want to record a
conversation that you

01:14:49.760 --> 01:14:51.480
have with someone else.

01:14:51.480 --> 01:14:54.085
That might not be the
best thing for everyone.

01:14:54.085 --> 01:14:55.960
GEORGE ZAIDAN: One of
the things you could do

01:14:55.960 --> 01:15:00.730
is instead of recording yourself
on camera, record just audio.

01:15:00.730 --> 01:15:02.410
Because the visual
part of it-- like

01:15:02.410 --> 01:15:04.701
if you're conscious that
there's a lens looking at you,

01:15:04.701 --> 01:15:05.949
it's very hard to be natural.

01:15:05.949 --> 01:15:07.490
AUDIENCE: Yeah, and
I'm not very good

01:15:07.490 --> 01:15:10.020
in front of a lens or anything.

01:15:10.020 --> 01:15:12.020
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Getting
rid of that misconception

01:15:12.020 --> 01:15:12.978
is a whole other thing.

01:15:12.978 --> 01:15:15.220
We'll get into it in a
second, but it's much easier

01:15:15.220 --> 01:15:17.780
to just be yourself if
you just have a mic,

01:15:17.780 --> 01:15:19.530
and you're not really--
you sort of forget

01:15:19.530 --> 01:15:20.446
that the mic is there.

01:15:20.446 --> 01:15:22.300
You're not looking into
a lens or whatever.

01:15:22.300 --> 01:15:26.910
So having that, it's easier
to record yourself and hear

01:15:26.910 --> 01:15:28.660
what you really sound
like if you just use

01:15:28.660 --> 01:15:32.260
audio, versus video as well.

01:15:32.260 --> 01:15:36.285
AUDIENCE: So say you're
trying to simplify something,

01:15:36.285 --> 01:15:39.340
a complicated concept, so
you're talking to [INAUDIBLE],

01:15:39.340 --> 01:15:43.830
and there's a lot of
different technical reasons

01:15:43.830 --> 01:15:49.410
that you have these
fin stabilizers.

01:15:49.410 --> 01:15:55.620
So just being able to
say that this is stopping

01:15:55.620 --> 01:15:58.690
the ship from
rolling, it's true,

01:15:58.690 --> 01:16:01.210
but there's other aspects to it.

01:16:01.210 --> 01:16:04.130
So this gets into
the accuracy portion.

01:16:04.130 --> 01:16:08.340
Like you could have a naval
architect go on K through 12

01:16:08.340 --> 01:16:11.090
and be like, yeah, but
there's more to it than that.

01:16:11.090 --> 01:16:13.012
So at what point are
you oversimplifying.

01:16:15.540 --> 01:16:23.700
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I think there's
no harm in alluding to the fact

01:16:23.700 --> 01:16:26.480
that there are that
you are just at the tip

01:16:26.480 --> 01:16:27.980
of the iceberg of information.

01:16:27.980 --> 01:16:29.907
So you could say
something like-- the way

01:16:29.907 --> 01:16:32.240
you said it was if you take
a cylinder, put it in water,

01:16:32.240 --> 01:16:33.255
and spin it, it'll spin.

01:16:33.255 --> 01:16:35.630
You take a cylinder, attach
some wings, put it in water--

01:16:35.630 --> 01:16:37.430
it's much harder to spin it.

01:16:37.430 --> 01:16:39.425
That is all 100%
accurate and true,

01:16:39.425 --> 01:16:41.550
but you don't get into any
of the technical reasons

01:16:41.550 --> 01:16:43.410
as to why that's the case.

01:16:43.410 --> 01:16:44.429
That's one way to do it.

01:16:44.429 --> 01:16:45.970
The other way to do
it is if you want

01:16:45.970 --> 01:16:47.712
to start talking about whys.

01:16:47.712 --> 01:16:50.170
And I don't know what the whys
are, so you have to help me,

01:16:50.170 --> 01:16:54.215
but you can start off
your senses with-- look,

01:16:54.215 --> 01:16:56.090
this is a really simple
way of explaining it,

01:16:56.090 --> 01:16:58.780
but basically, blah, blah,
blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:16:58.780 --> 01:17:00.810
So you just sort of
allude to the fact

01:17:00.810 --> 01:17:04.410
that I'm giving you the
super simple version of it.

01:17:04.410 --> 01:17:07.350
It's much more complicated
than this in real life.

01:17:07.350 --> 01:17:10.030
And you can even explain
what those complications are.

01:17:10.030 --> 01:17:13.700
So if you had wings with
a bunch of holes in them,

01:17:13.700 --> 01:17:17.250
they wouldn't be as
effective as solid wings,

01:17:17.250 --> 01:17:18.520
because x, y, or z.

01:17:18.520 --> 01:17:22.140
Or if your ship's
wings need to be

01:17:22.140 --> 01:17:24.720
able to do this and that
for whatever reason--

01:17:24.720 --> 01:17:27.911
you can allude to stuff
without actually explaining it,

01:17:27.911 --> 01:17:29.910
and that's OK, because
you do that in real life.

01:17:29.910 --> 01:17:32.330
If you're sitting across
the table from someone

01:17:32.330 --> 01:17:35.050
and explaining something to
them, the first time you do it,

01:17:35.050 --> 01:17:39.590
you're not going to be like--
roman numeral I, part a,

01:17:39.590 --> 01:17:41.847
subsection b-- you're not
going to go super in-depth.

01:17:41.847 --> 01:17:44.180
You're going to be like look,
here's the important thing

01:17:44.180 --> 01:17:45.302
to get right now.

01:17:45.302 --> 01:17:46.510
Here are some of the details.

01:17:46.510 --> 01:17:50.134
We can about the details later,
but this is the crucial thing.

01:17:50.134 --> 01:17:52.519
AUDIENCE: So more of the
result and not everything

01:17:52.519 --> 01:17:54.771
that got to that result?

01:17:54.771 --> 01:17:56.521
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I don't
know that I would--

01:17:56.521 --> 01:17:59.167
AUDIENCE: Or if it's
a little too tricky,

01:17:59.167 --> 01:18:03.170
then mention it, but focus
on what the main reason

01:18:03.170 --> 01:18:03.920
why they're there.

01:18:03.920 --> 01:18:04.753
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Yeah.

01:18:04.753 --> 01:18:08.780
I think just being conscious
of the fact that what you're

01:18:08.780 --> 01:18:11.640
presenting isn't all
of the information,

01:18:11.640 --> 01:18:14.370
it is an accurate portion
of the information.

01:18:14.370 --> 01:18:16.064
AUDIENCE: And
that's actually what

01:18:16.064 --> 01:18:17.393
we want with Science Out Loud.

01:18:17.393 --> 01:18:19.268
And keep in mind, it's
a very different style

01:18:19.268 --> 01:18:20.777
than some of the
other videos that i

01:18:20.777 --> 01:18:22.610
was talking about on
the first day of class.

01:18:22.610 --> 01:18:24.520
But we want to pique curiosity.

01:18:24.520 --> 01:18:27.520
We want people to finish
watching the video

01:18:27.520 --> 01:18:29.650
and ask themselves
those questions

01:18:29.650 --> 01:18:32.147
and try to figure
it out on their own

01:18:32.147 --> 01:18:33.480
and explore the other resources.

01:18:33.480 --> 01:18:35.021
And that's a very
different objective

01:18:35.021 --> 01:18:38.717
than say a lecture video
or a technical video.

01:18:38.717 --> 01:18:39.800
So just keep that in mind.

01:18:39.800 --> 01:18:42.802
Again, whatever best practices
we're establishing here

01:18:42.802 --> 01:18:44.260
aren't necessarily
ones that you'll

01:18:44.260 --> 01:18:48.110
carry over to every
single educational video.

01:18:48.110 --> 01:18:51.440
We encompass such a
huge variety, right?

01:18:51.440 --> 01:18:55.090
But I think that's true of
even the most technical video.

01:18:55.090 --> 01:18:58.450
And again, this goes back to the
whole rabbit hole witness test.

01:18:58.450 --> 01:19:02.060
Once you find yourself
clarifying more and more

01:19:02.060 --> 01:19:03.880
to the point where
you found yourself

01:19:03.880 --> 01:19:07.630
on a topic that is tangential
to the main point of your video

01:19:07.630 --> 01:19:09.620
or the main point
of your lesson,

01:19:09.620 --> 01:19:13.520
then it's time to backtrack
a little bit, and that's OK.

01:19:13.520 --> 01:19:15.690
No video under an hour.

01:19:15.690 --> 01:19:18.850
No semester-long class
is going to answer

01:19:18.850 --> 01:19:20.650
every single question
that's related

01:19:20.650 --> 01:19:24.570
to the topic of the class.

01:19:24.570 --> 01:19:26.765
AUDIENCE: But this gets
back to what we were

01:19:26.765 --> 01:19:28.030
talking about the [INAUDIBLE].

01:19:28.030 --> 01:19:31.610
By going deeply and
narrowing your focus actually

01:19:31.610 --> 01:19:34.820
allows you to allude to a
lot of much larger topics

01:19:34.820 --> 01:19:36.230
superficially.

01:19:36.230 --> 01:19:38.700
And people get it more
quickly the more narrow

01:19:38.700 --> 01:19:40.470
you are in your examples.

01:19:40.470 --> 01:19:43.530
And think if there were a
truth in here, that's the truth

01:19:43.530 --> 01:19:46.877
to sort of apply-- is that
the more specific and narrow

01:19:46.877 --> 01:19:48.460
you can be without
getting [INAUDIBLE]

01:19:48.460 --> 01:19:50.710
in that extra
information, the easier it

01:19:50.710 --> 01:19:52.830
is to allude to that
extra information

01:19:52.830 --> 01:19:54.610
without it-- like
a story flow, you

01:19:54.610 --> 01:19:56.680
want it always more forward.

01:19:56.680 --> 01:19:59.840
And if this information
is so little

01:19:59.840 --> 01:20:03.350
that it doesn't prevent
the forward motion

01:20:03.350 --> 01:20:06.720
of your storyline, then
you know you're doing

01:20:06.720 --> 01:20:08.199
a good job of including that.

01:20:08.199 --> 01:20:09.990
What you don't want is
for this information

01:20:09.990 --> 01:20:13.027
to take you backwards
or sideways.

01:20:13.027 --> 01:20:15.360
AUDIENCE: I mean I guess I
should rephrase that it's not

01:20:15.360 --> 01:20:16.443
necessarily a rabbit hole.

01:20:16.443 --> 01:20:19.400
You don't want to
branch out too much.

01:20:19.400 --> 01:20:23.650
You want accuracy, specificity
to a certain degree.

01:20:23.650 --> 01:20:28.270
You could very well do a
video on why do boats float,

01:20:28.270 --> 01:20:30.586
but that wouldn't
really be a good video.

01:20:30.586 --> 01:20:32.210
It wouldn't be a very
compelling video.

01:20:32.210 --> 01:20:35.480
So you're going to make a video
about the wings on a boat.

01:20:35.480 --> 01:20:38.750
You're going to hit the bigger
topic of how things float,

01:20:38.750 --> 01:20:41.242
but that's not the thing that's
driving your video forward.

01:20:41.242 --> 01:20:42.700
AUDIENCE: And that's
why your topic

01:20:42.700 --> 01:20:48.410
is perfectly narrow
of imagining three

01:20:48.410 --> 01:20:51.890
differently smooshed shoeboxes.

01:20:51.890 --> 01:20:55.230
Why does this one versus
this one-- and it's

01:20:55.230 --> 01:20:57.590
a narrow enough topic,
and concrete enough

01:20:57.590 --> 01:20:59.900
that it will allow you to
get to some of those bigger

01:20:59.900 --> 01:21:03.100
sink or float buoyancy
design issues.

01:21:03.100 --> 01:21:08.052
But using this very small way
of getting access to that.

01:21:08.052 --> 01:21:09.510
GEORGE ZAIDAN: By
the way, I wanted

01:21:09.510 --> 01:21:13.660
to come back to something
that is a tad tangential,

01:21:13.660 --> 01:21:15.570
ironically.

01:21:15.570 --> 01:21:19.660
You said, maybe it's better
then to just tell the results

01:21:19.660 --> 01:21:21.080
and leave out the process.

01:21:21.080 --> 01:21:22.460
And I said no, maybe not.

01:21:22.460 --> 01:21:26.870
The reason that I said
no is because sometimes,

01:21:26.870 --> 01:21:29.190
taking your audience through
the experimentation that

01:21:29.190 --> 01:21:31.085
was done to get to
a result is just

01:21:31.085 --> 01:21:32.710
as interesting or
even more interesting

01:21:32.710 --> 01:21:33.930
as the result itself.

01:21:33.930 --> 01:21:38.619
So the Stephen Hawking example--
the time travel experiment

01:21:38.619 --> 01:21:40.660
and the intricacies of
the time travel experiment

01:21:40.660 --> 01:21:42.680
are just as interesting,
to me, anyway,

01:21:42.680 --> 01:21:45.901
as the result of that
experiment, whatever it is.

01:21:45.901 --> 01:21:48.150
So that's why I would just
caution against using that.

01:21:48.150 --> 01:21:53.720
Sometimes-- how did
people first invent

01:21:53.720 --> 01:21:55.256
compartmentalizing boats?

01:21:55.256 --> 01:21:57.130
I'm not saying that is
an interesting answer.

01:21:57.130 --> 01:21:57.790
It may not be.

01:21:57.790 --> 01:22:01.250
But sometimes that process is
just as interesting as the fact

01:22:01.250 --> 01:22:04.237
that there are compartmentalized
boats and why they work.

01:22:04.237 --> 01:22:05.820
AUDIENCE: One thing
that I mentioned--

01:22:05.820 --> 01:22:07.530
I don't know if
it's worth exploring

01:22:07.530 --> 01:22:12.720
is the whole reason why
[INAUDIBLE] was like I know

01:22:12.720 --> 01:22:17.890
that floating is obviously
a big teaching point,

01:22:17.890 --> 01:22:21.530
but if you open with
why the Titanic sank,

01:22:21.530 --> 01:22:26.680
which has exactly to do
with compartmentalization,

01:22:26.680 --> 01:22:29.610
is that something that
would be a better hook?

01:22:29.610 --> 01:22:34.080
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I honestly
like your shoebox better.

01:22:34.080 --> 01:22:36.140
I'll tell you why--
because it's more visual.

01:22:36.140 --> 01:22:38.496
Sorry, it's more visual
because it has you in it.

01:22:38.496 --> 01:22:39.120
There's a demo.

01:22:39.120 --> 01:22:40.828
There's a thing that
someone can look at,

01:22:40.828 --> 01:22:42.570
and it's directly accessible.

01:22:42.570 --> 01:22:45.200
With the Titanic,
yeah, it's an example

01:22:45.200 --> 01:22:47.040
that everyone knows,
and you could maybe

01:22:47.040 --> 01:22:50.110
use stock footage of the
movie Titanic or whatever.

01:22:50.110 --> 01:22:53.960
But it's one degree
of complexity--

01:22:53.960 --> 01:22:56.110
it starts at a higher
level of complexity

01:22:56.110 --> 01:22:57.892
than your shoebox example.

01:22:57.892 --> 01:22:59.614
AUDIENCE: Well I'm
saying you could do--

01:22:59.614 --> 01:23:01.405
GEORGE ZAIDAN: First
shoebox, then Titanic?

01:23:01.405 --> 01:23:04.390
AUDIENCE: No, how the Titanic
did their compartmentalization

01:23:04.390 --> 01:23:06.525
with a shoebox.

01:23:06.525 --> 01:23:08.150
So they didn't finish
their [INAUDIBLE]

01:23:08.150 --> 01:23:10.260
to the deck, which you
