01:23:56.250 --> 01:24:00.600
and if you weren't actually
an engineer, just maybe

01:24:00.600 --> 01:24:02.100
Vsauce or hand Hank
Green, then I'd

01:24:02.100 --> 01:24:04.170
say, yeah, talk about
why the Titanic sunk.

01:24:04.170 --> 01:24:06.320
But it's a story that's
already been told.

01:24:06.320 --> 01:24:08.570
And it's a story that
can be told by anyone.

01:24:08.570 --> 01:24:10.640
You have this
opportunity to tell us

01:24:10.640 --> 01:24:13.135
a story from a perspective
that not many very people can,

01:24:13.135 --> 01:24:14.760
and that's what I
was trying to get out

01:24:14.760 --> 01:24:17.350
on the first day about being
able to take yourself out

01:24:17.350 --> 01:24:19.890
of the perspective that
you're used to having.

01:24:19.890 --> 01:24:23.370
I think that is an opportunity
to capitalize upon, for sure.

01:24:23.370 --> 01:24:25.740
So it's not that I think
that the Titanic thing is

01:24:25.740 --> 01:24:28.490
a bad hook, necessarily--
just that the one you have

01:24:28.490 --> 01:24:30.090
is so much better.

01:24:30.090 --> 01:24:33.286
And one that not
other people can do.

01:24:33.286 --> 01:24:34.660
AUDIENCE: Can I
also say that you

01:24:34.660 --> 01:24:37.330
had mentioned about process.

01:24:37.330 --> 01:24:41.620
In my lab, the work that
I see predominately-- I

01:24:41.620 --> 01:24:44.350
would actually argue that it's
extremely hard for scientists

01:24:44.350 --> 01:24:50.350
to share a process in
an interesting way.

01:24:50.350 --> 01:24:53.860
That scientists, typically--
and I am generalizing,

01:24:53.860 --> 01:24:56.950
and this is not really fair, but
because we spend so much time

01:24:56.950 --> 01:24:58.750
day-to-day going
through a process,

01:24:58.750 --> 01:25:00.660
you want to share
it chronologically,

01:25:00.660 --> 01:25:03.200
and that's where your default
is to go from start to finish,

01:25:03.200 --> 01:25:07.080
telling people what you
did in painstaking detail,

01:25:07.080 --> 01:25:08.290
and that's boring.

01:25:08.290 --> 01:25:10.670
And so that's really,
really hard-- if any of you

01:25:10.670 --> 01:25:14.570
end up doing a process where
you're sharing your process,

01:25:14.570 --> 01:25:18.290
it's really hard to figure
out the bigger picture

01:25:18.290 --> 01:25:22.900
within the process so
that an outsider actually

01:25:22.900 --> 01:25:25.120
finds your process
interesting, as opposed

01:25:25.120 --> 01:25:27.550
to just sharing the I did
this, then I did this,

01:25:27.550 --> 01:25:29.470
then I did this.

01:25:29.470 --> 01:25:31.400
Explaining why I did
what I did each way

01:25:31.400 --> 01:25:32.650
is what people care about.

01:25:32.650 --> 01:25:34.316
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Well
the interesting part

01:25:34.316 --> 01:25:40.330
is the moment of ingenuity that
led to an experiment designed

01:25:40.330 --> 01:25:41.820
the way it was designed.

01:25:41.820 --> 01:25:43.660
Not the day-to-day--

01:25:43.660 --> 01:25:46.170
AUDIENCE: Exactly, and I
feel like because people

01:25:46.170 --> 01:25:48.740
in their labs are like
someone needs to listen to me.

01:25:48.740 --> 01:25:49.680
I did this.

01:25:49.680 --> 01:25:52.799
It didn't work, and I spent
hours and hours working on this

01:25:52.799 --> 01:25:53.590
and it didn't work.

01:25:53.590 --> 01:25:56.290
They feel like they want
to share that with people,

01:25:56.290 --> 01:25:59.030
but people don't
actually care about that.

01:25:59.030 --> 01:26:00.760
They care about the
why you designed

01:26:00.760 --> 01:26:03.300
the experiment that way,
and why it didn't work,

01:26:03.300 --> 01:26:05.700
as opposed to the
what you actually did,

01:26:05.700 --> 01:26:09.070
the who cares kind of concept.

01:26:09.070 --> 01:26:13.870
AUDIENCE: Actually, I agree
with you on the Titanic idea,

01:26:13.870 --> 01:26:18.190
but you mentioned that you could
build these compartments out

01:26:18.190 --> 01:26:21.185
of shoeboxes, and I think
that at least the kids that we

01:26:21.185 --> 01:26:22.560
talked to yesterday--
they really

01:26:22.560 --> 01:26:24.851
like the idea of destruction.

01:26:24.851 --> 01:26:27.860
Something burning,
being crushed.

01:26:27.860 --> 01:26:30.010
So if you could kind of
talk about those concepts

01:26:30.010 --> 01:26:34.150
and in the end, you
sink some random ship.

01:26:34.150 --> 01:26:37.180
That would kind of show,
first of all, that it's cool,

01:26:37.180 --> 01:26:40.850
but also it shows that what
you;re talking about is

01:26:40.850 --> 01:26:41.350
important.

01:26:41.350 --> 01:26:42.210
AUDIENCE: Don't get me wrong.

01:26:42.210 --> 01:26:43.710
You can totally
bring up the Titanic

01:26:43.710 --> 01:26:47.080
at the end as the bigger
picture application.

01:26:47.080 --> 01:26:48.460
That's awesome.

01:26:48.460 --> 01:26:51.650
It's just the hook
isn't the place for it,

01:26:51.650 --> 01:26:53.600
I think personally.

01:26:53.600 --> 01:26:56.010
GEORGE ZAIDAN: It's
been done before.

01:26:56.010 --> 01:26:57.035
I agree with you.

01:26:57.035 --> 01:26:57.910
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Great.

01:26:57.910 --> 01:27:01.630
Anything else on this script?

