01:34:56.710 --> 01:34:58.550
It's going to hurt.

01:34:58.550 --> 01:35:00.930
You know you've got these like
metal wires in your mouth.

01:35:00.930 --> 01:35:02.860
What happens if they
poke you in the gum?

01:35:02.860 --> 01:35:05.990
How you going to talk with
all this stuff in your face?

01:35:05.990 --> 01:35:07.960
People are going
to make fun of you.

01:35:07.960 --> 01:35:10.580
Those are actual,
real fears that you

01:35:10.580 --> 01:35:12.320
get when you've had braces.

01:35:12.320 --> 01:35:16.830
So, pointing them out
like that is effective.

01:35:16.830 --> 01:35:17.916
What else?

01:35:17.916 --> 01:35:19.541
AUDIENCE: Just to
check, is the content

01:35:19.541 --> 01:35:21.874
of the question or the video
why you get braces or is it

01:35:21.874 --> 01:35:23.189
[INAUDIBLE]?

01:35:23.189 --> 01:35:24.817
AUDIENCE: The
actual video itself

01:35:24.817 --> 01:35:28.608
is about what happens
when the braces move

01:35:28.608 --> 01:35:32.018
your teeth on a cellular level.

01:35:32.018 --> 01:35:33.476
AUDIENCE: What
happens [INAUDIBLE]?

01:35:38.581 --> 01:35:40.580
AUDIENCE: As the force
is applied to your tooth,

01:35:40.580 --> 01:35:46.910
there are two different
types of cells, one of which

01:35:46.910 --> 01:35:49.570
actually dissolves some
of the bone in your jaw

01:35:49.570 --> 01:35:52.588
to make a little bit more room,
and another one that actually

01:35:52.588 --> 01:35:55.689
builds the bone to be able
to hold the bone in place.

01:35:55.689 --> 01:35:56.480
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Wow.

01:35:56.480 --> 01:35:57.240
I had no idea.

01:35:57.240 --> 01:35:59.090
That's cool.

01:35:59.090 --> 01:36:02.934
AUDIENCE: And that's
like the shoebox thing.

01:36:02.934 --> 01:36:04.350
GEORGE ZAIDAN:
That's the reaction

01:36:04.350 --> 01:36:05.970
you want from an audience.

01:36:05.970 --> 01:36:08.230
What I just did--
I wasn't faking it.

01:36:08.230 --> 01:36:09.670
That's an authentic reaction.

01:36:09.670 --> 01:36:11.415
That's the reaction
that you want.

01:36:11.415 --> 01:36:13.290
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I mean
later on in the script

01:36:13.290 --> 01:36:17.590
I say it's actually
dissolving your jaw.

01:36:17.590 --> 01:36:19.520
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I
had a question--

01:36:19.520 --> 01:36:25.180
so the braces are only
attached to your teeth, right?

01:36:25.180 --> 01:36:27.230
So normally when you
want to move something--

01:36:27.230 --> 01:36:31.130
like I want to move this
table-- my foot's on the floor,

01:36:31.130 --> 01:36:34.520
and I push against my
foot to pull the table,

01:36:34.520 --> 01:36:39.580
whereas with braces, I'm not
holding some external object

01:36:39.580 --> 01:36:43.667
to pull teeth in a certain
direction, so how is that by--

01:36:43.667 --> 01:36:44.541
AUDIENCE: Headgear.

01:36:44.541 --> 01:36:44.980
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Huh?

01:36:44.980 --> 01:36:45.470
AUDIENCE: Headgear.

01:36:45.470 --> 01:36:46.720
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Headgear, yeah.

01:36:46.720 --> 01:36:48.890
But most people
don't-- I don't know.

01:36:48.890 --> 01:36:51.066
Correct me if I'm wrong,
but I think people--

01:36:51.066 --> 01:36:52.440
when you get
braces, usually it's

01:36:52.440 --> 01:36:55.530
just the metal and the
wire on your tooth.

01:36:55.530 --> 01:36:57.990
But there's no
external support there.

01:36:57.990 --> 01:36:59.640
So how does it move your teeth?

01:36:59.640 --> 01:37:01.320
AUDIENCE: So that's
a physics question,

01:37:01.320 --> 01:37:03.170
and we went over this yesterday.

01:37:03.170 --> 01:37:06.790
Because there are
different aspects.

01:37:06.790 --> 01:37:08.290
There's the sort
of what's happening

01:37:08.290 --> 01:37:10.890
on the cellular level,
which is one approach.

01:37:10.890 --> 01:37:15.350
You can also do it from the
material science-- basically

01:37:15.350 --> 01:37:18.250
what moves your
teeth the wire itself

01:37:18.250 --> 01:37:22.566
and its shape that's
constantly applying pressure.

01:37:22.566 --> 01:37:24.774
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Is that why
you get your wire changed?

01:37:24.774 --> 01:37:25.740
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:37:25.740 --> 01:37:28.440
AUDIENCE: I mean imagine
being one person who

01:37:28.440 --> 01:37:30.440
has two boxes on
either side of them,

01:37:30.440 --> 01:37:33.590
and they want to bring
them closer together.

01:37:33.590 --> 01:37:36.280
The external force is the person
itself pulling them together.

01:37:36.280 --> 01:37:39.040
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Yeah, but
the tension in the wire--

01:37:39.040 --> 01:37:39.640
that's the--

01:37:39.640 --> 01:37:40.750
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:37:40.750 --> 01:37:43.901
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] when I
had braces they had my molars--

01:37:43.901 --> 01:37:46.400
I don't know if they're using
that now to the points or not,

01:37:46.400 --> 01:37:48.095
but you had the metal--

01:37:48.095 --> 01:37:49.110
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:37:49.110 --> 01:37:51.045
AUDIENCE: They put a
whole band around your--

01:37:51.045 --> 01:37:52.170
they don't do that anymore.

01:37:52.170 --> 01:37:54.630
AUDIENCE: They don't--
back in my day.

01:37:54.630 --> 01:37:55.284
[LAUGHTER]

01:37:55.284 --> 01:37:57.200
AUDIENCE: They have much
better adhesives now,

01:37:57.200 --> 01:38:00.700
so that was another-- the
chemistry of the epoxy

01:38:00.700 --> 01:38:03.594
that actually-- I mean
there's a lot of science that

01:38:03.594 --> 01:38:04.510
goes into your braces.

01:38:04.510 --> 01:38:06.550
AUDIENCE: And when
you think about it--

01:38:06.550 --> 01:38:08.500
I would have this discussion
with my mother all the time,

01:38:08.500 --> 01:38:09.958
because I had to
have braces twice.

01:38:09.958 --> 01:38:11.360
And I was like, mom.

01:38:11.360 --> 01:38:14.110
Braces, when you think about
it, they're like barbaric.

01:38:14.110 --> 01:38:16.210
I can't believe we're
living in the 21st century,

01:38:16.210 --> 01:38:22.120
and I pay money for a person
to glue metal to my mouth

01:38:22.120 --> 01:38:25.470
and take wires to
yank my teeth together

01:38:25.470 --> 01:38:27.190
because I have too
much gap in-between.

01:38:27.190 --> 01:38:29.620
That's so barbaric when
you think about it,

01:38:29.620 --> 01:38:31.860
that your jaw is dissolving.

01:38:31.860 --> 01:38:36.150
But barbaric in a way that's
fascinating to watch on video,

01:38:36.150 --> 01:38:38.880
and I feel like
that's such a more

01:38:38.880 --> 01:38:46.000
high-stakes drama-driven hook
than you're worrying if braces

01:38:46.000 --> 01:38:47.820
will hurt or how you'll look.

01:38:47.820 --> 01:38:50.278
AUDIENCE: It's interesting too,
because the bottom question

01:38:50.278 --> 01:38:56.150
gets at the anthropological
question of what is beauty.

01:38:56.150 --> 01:38:59.289
But really, I think
it's much more.

01:38:59.289 --> 01:39:01.580
If we're going to get back
to the evolutionary question

01:39:01.580 --> 01:39:03.795
of what makes someone
cold versus hot, and will

01:39:03.795 --> 01:39:06.080
they die soon or
not-- if all of us

01:39:06.080 --> 01:39:11.040
has evolved to the point
where 80% of tweens

01:39:11.040 --> 01:39:14.070
end up getting braces, what's
wrong with our society,

01:39:14.070 --> 01:39:16.620
and why do we have to
keep fixing these teeth?

01:39:16.620 --> 01:39:18.869
Is it actually going
to make us die sooner

01:39:18.869 --> 01:39:20.410
if you don't fix
your teeth, or is it

01:39:20.410 --> 01:39:22.420
just because we look prettier?

01:39:22.420 --> 01:39:23.910
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Is it cosmetic?

01:39:23.910 --> 01:39:25.020
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:39:25.020 --> 01:39:26.882
I know that I will
at some point have

01:39:26.882 --> 01:39:29.090
to deal with some more
significant dental issues that

01:39:29.090 --> 01:39:31.700
are actually about
my functioning.

01:39:31.700 --> 01:39:35.610
But proportion of this is
actually-- I don't know.

01:39:35.610 --> 01:39:38.056
And I don't know if that's
a question you're even

01:39:38.056 --> 01:39:41.630
going to get into, but why
do so many teenagers end up

01:39:41.630 --> 01:39:42.560
getting braces.

01:39:42.560 --> 01:39:49.710
GEORGE ZAIDAN: So that and
Elizabeth's point are related.

01:39:49.710 --> 01:39:53.770
When she was describing
the barbarity of you

01:39:53.770 --> 01:39:56.270
get these metal blocks
and a wire in your mouth

01:39:56.270 --> 01:39:58.270
and all sorts of stuff--
what technique is that?

01:39:58.270 --> 01:39:58.910
What is that?

01:39:58.910 --> 01:40:00.030
It's not a metaphor.

01:40:00.030 --> 01:40:03.400
What is she doing there?

01:40:03.400 --> 01:40:05.230
Yeah, so she's
inducing emotional pain

01:40:05.230 --> 01:40:07.870
by asking you to put yourself
in her shoes and getting this.

01:40:07.870 --> 01:40:12.030
But specifically when she
says, OK, you get braces.

01:40:12.030 --> 01:40:14.020
You're going to go
and have someone--

01:40:14.020 --> 01:40:17.710
you're going to pay
them to glue metal stuff

01:40:17.710 --> 01:40:20.095
to every one of your teeth,
then take a wire that is not

01:40:20.095 --> 01:40:22.720
in the shape of your mouth, bend
it so that it fits your mouth,

01:40:22.720 --> 01:40:25.500
and then it forces your
teeth to move around.

01:40:25.500 --> 01:40:27.640
Like what is that
that she's doing?

01:40:27.640 --> 01:40:29.990
Who here has seen
Robin Williams' comedy

01:40:29.990 --> 01:40:31.220
sketch on golf?

01:40:31.220 --> 01:40:33.810
Anyone?

01:40:33.810 --> 01:40:34.630
Oh, you have?

01:40:34.630 --> 01:40:37.360
It has a lot of bad language
in it, but it is hilarious.

01:40:37.360 --> 01:40:39.000
And I can't do it
here for that reason,

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:41.630
but you should watch it tonight.

01:40:41.630 --> 01:40:45.800
He basically says,
look, golf-- you

01:40:45.800 --> 01:40:50.380
take a stick with a really tiny
metal thing on the end of it,

01:40:50.380 --> 01:40:52.230
and you have a small ball.

01:40:52.230 --> 01:40:55.250
And the goal is, without
touching the ball,

01:40:55.250 --> 01:40:58.200
to beat it with
the stick until you

01:40:58.200 --> 01:41:01.680
get close enough to a
tiny hole in the ground

01:41:01.680 --> 01:41:04.150
that you can take
another stick and then

01:41:04.150 --> 01:41:08.882
gently tap the ball into the
hole, not once, but 18 times.

01:41:08.882 --> 01:41:10.840
That's the same technique
as Elizabeth's using,

01:41:10.840 --> 01:41:12.000
what is that?

01:41:12.000 --> 01:41:13.150
Why is that interesting?

01:41:13.150 --> 01:41:18.050
Why does that make us listen?

01:41:18.050 --> 01:41:18.956
Yeah?

01:41:18.956 --> 01:41:20.330
AUDIENCE: Well
it's was humorous,

01:41:20.330 --> 01:41:23.870
because you get used to the
jargon and different terms,

01:41:23.870 --> 01:41:27.180
but it's the sort of thing if
you're trying to describe it

01:41:27.180 --> 01:41:29.830
to someone who has no clue
what you're talking about.

01:41:29.830 --> 01:41:31.680
it just sounds so
utterly ridiculous.

01:41:31.680 --> 01:41:32.638
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Exactly.

01:41:32.638 --> 01:41:35.740
So the humor, actually, I'd
argue is a secondary component.

01:41:35.740 --> 01:41:37.620
Really, the crux of
it is what you said

01:41:37.620 --> 01:41:39.080
about being used to something.

01:41:39.080 --> 01:41:41.800
It is taking something
that's familiar

01:41:41.800 --> 01:41:46.490
and describing it from a
completely different vantage

01:41:46.490 --> 01:41:49.880
point, and you can only
do that with things

01:41:49.880 --> 01:41:52.210
that are familiar enough
that people are so used

01:41:52.210 --> 01:41:54.920
to them that they just don't
think about it-- braces,

01:41:54.920 --> 01:41:55.420
oh yeah.

01:41:55.420 --> 01:41:57.540
Braces, whatever.

01:41:57.540 --> 01:41:59.620
But when you shift
that perspective,

01:41:59.620 --> 01:42:01.270
you do inject humor.

01:42:01.270 --> 01:42:03.190
You can inject drama.

01:42:03.190 --> 01:42:07.750
You can inject--
mainly humor and drama.

01:42:07.750 --> 01:42:08.697
Humor and drama.

01:42:08.697 --> 01:42:11.280
And you force people to sort of
step out of their comfort zone

01:42:11.280 --> 01:42:13.420
and consider something
that-- they just

01:42:13.420 --> 01:42:18.390
look at it in a totally
different way, which

01:42:18.390 --> 01:42:20.550
is an alternative opening.

01:42:20.550 --> 01:42:22.840
So that's another thing
that you could consider.

01:42:22.840 --> 01:42:24.700
If I were to tell
you-- and the way to do

01:42:24.700 --> 01:42:26.765
it would be to do
it as a reveal.

01:42:26.765 --> 01:42:28.140
If I were to tell
you that you're

01:42:28.140 --> 01:42:30.990
going to go to someone's
place of business,

01:42:30.990 --> 01:42:34.200
pay them money to fill your
mouth with a bunch of metal

01:42:34.200 --> 01:42:39.290
and plastic and chemicals,
would you do it?

01:42:39.290 --> 01:42:40.102
And then like, no.

01:42:40.102 --> 01:42:41.310
But people do that every day.

01:42:41.310 --> 01:42:42.910
It's called getting braces.

01:42:42.910 --> 01:42:45.200
The way I just did
it was not very good,

01:42:45.200 --> 01:42:48.340
but you get the general idea.

01:42:48.340 --> 01:42:49.816
Other comments?

01:42:49.816 --> 01:42:51.964
AUDIENCE: I also
liked-- I was actually

01:42:51.964 --> 01:42:53.952
with Andrea when
she was pitching

01:42:53.952 --> 01:42:55.620
her idea to sixth graders.

01:42:55.620 --> 01:43:00.690
And her first question
was do you have braces?

01:43:00.690 --> 01:43:04.940
And this one girl who did-- she
was really excited about that.

01:43:04.940 --> 01:43:06.156
Like yes, this is about me.

01:43:06.156 --> 01:43:08.780
And then the next question was,
well, do you know what they do?

01:43:08.780 --> 01:43:11.890
And she started pitching
all these ideas.

01:43:11.890 --> 01:43:15.339
This is what I think they
do, but then the answer

01:43:15.339 --> 01:43:16.130
was very different.

01:43:20.800 --> 01:43:22.745
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Sorry--
the girl thought

01:43:22.745 --> 01:43:24.370
they did something
completely different

01:43:24.370 --> 01:43:25.328
than they actually did?

01:43:25.328 --> 01:43:27.070
What did she think they did?

01:43:27.070 --> 01:43:30.860
She just kind of said pushing
teeth, whatever-- just a really

01:43:30.860 --> 01:43:31.560
basic answer.

01:43:31.560 --> 01:43:33.770
But then Andrea
was saying there's

01:43:33.770 --> 01:43:36.050
so much they actually do.

01:43:36.050 --> 01:43:38.260
And I thought that
was a really good way

01:43:38.260 --> 01:43:40.310
to get into it, because
they got really excited,

01:43:40.310 --> 01:43:43.630
and they started talking about
their experience with braces.

01:43:43.630 --> 01:43:45.890
So here it's kind
of-- if you say maybe

01:43:45.890 --> 01:43:48.130
instead of whether
it's worrying,

01:43:48.130 --> 01:43:51.180
you could say do you worry
about how much it will hurt?

01:43:51.180 --> 01:43:53.840
All these things.

01:43:53.840 --> 01:43:57.460
Get the audience thinking
maybe offering their own ideas,

01:43:57.460 --> 01:44:02.387
but also it connects them to--
this is something that I have.

01:44:02.387 --> 01:44:03.220
GEORGE ZAIDAN: Yeah.

01:44:03.220 --> 01:44:06.230
So that approach--
generally, I would call it

01:44:06.230 --> 01:44:08.240
the preconceived
notion approach.

01:44:08.240 --> 01:44:12.510
So you basically guess or
know what your audience thinks

01:44:12.510 --> 01:44:16.569
about something, and usually
that is either entirely wrong,

01:44:16.569 --> 01:44:18.860
or parts of it are wrong, or
not complete, or whatever.

01:44:18.860 --> 01:44:22.580
And you say you start the video
by saying you probably think

01:44:22.580 --> 01:44:25.620
that x, but actually y.

01:44:25.620 --> 01:44:27.510
Or z or whatever.

01:44:27.510 --> 01:44:32.510
And so that is another-- it's
very different than the fill

01:44:32.510 --> 01:44:34.810
your mouth with a bunch of
metal and wires and stuff,

01:44:34.810 --> 01:44:37.410
but it can be just as engaging
and interesting, depending

01:44:37.410 --> 01:44:40.130
on what the subject matter is.

01:44:40.130 --> 01:44:42.090
The only difference--
and this is

01:44:42.090 --> 01:44:45.010
where you've got to be careful--
is that when you're actually

01:44:45.010 --> 01:44:46.930
in a room interacting
with people,

01:44:46.930 --> 01:44:49.920
going back and forth with
the Socratic method is great,

01:44:49.920 --> 01:44:52.300
and it is a perfect way
to get into the topic,

01:44:52.300 --> 01:44:55.260
but you can't do
that with video.

01:44:55.260 --> 01:44:57.100
And so you what you
don't want to do

01:44:57.100 --> 01:45:04.420
is make that two dimensional
conversation one dimension

01:45:04.420 --> 01:45:07.420
by sort of just stripping
the away the kids' answers

01:45:07.420 --> 01:45:09.040
and just putting
in the questions.

01:45:14.730 --> 01:45:19.360
It's kind of like trying to fit
a square peg into a round hole,

01:45:19.360 --> 01:45:23.177
or the other way around in
the sense that it's designed

01:45:23.177 --> 01:45:25.468
for one medium, and you're
trying to use it in another.

01:45:25.468 --> 01:45:28.250
[? SEAM ?] And I know that's
not a great way of explaining

01:45:28.250 --> 01:45:31.001
why it doesn't fully work,
and I don't necessarily

01:45:31.001 --> 01:45:32.334
have a better way of explaining.

01:45:32.334 --> 01:45:35.690
AUDIENCE: Isn't that why
Dora and why Blues Clues

01:45:35.690 --> 01:45:37.606
are held the way
that they are, where

01:45:37.606 --> 01:45:39.400
it's like a rhetorical
question, but they

01:45:39.400 --> 01:45:41.220
leave space for the
kids to-- my son

01:45:41.220 --> 01:45:42.678
watches and answers
the television.

01:45:42.678 --> 01:45:45.010
AUDIENCE: And that's the
educational best practices

01:45:45.010 --> 01:45:46.732
for educational videos
that I was talking about

01:45:46.732 --> 01:45:48.357
on the first day--
that you acknowledge

01:45:48.357 --> 01:45:50.930
your audience, that you
give room for interaction.

01:45:50.930 --> 01:45:55.330
I will say, going
out of your comment,

01:45:55.330 --> 01:45:58.670
and sort of addressing
the kids where they are--

01:45:58.670 --> 01:46:02.760
don't forget about
George's point of talking

01:46:02.760 --> 01:46:06.060
for the audience, not to them.

01:46:06.060 --> 01:46:11.490
Because the overall point I
would say about the wording

01:46:11.490 --> 01:46:18.960
and the set-up of this opening
is that a sixth grade kid would

01:46:18.960 --> 01:46:21.730
be interested in
this, but I'm not sure

01:46:21.730 --> 01:46:25.850
that their parent would
necessarily be relate.

01:46:25.850 --> 01:46:29.240
And maybe it's just the way
the questions are posed,

01:46:29.240 --> 01:46:32.730
or the types of
questions that are asked,

01:46:32.730 --> 01:46:36.650
but there's a risk of
falling into this tone

01:46:36.650 --> 01:46:37.925
of like after-school special.

01:46:41.420 --> 01:46:42.030
I don't know.

01:46:42.030 --> 01:46:44.370
George, do you have
tangible feedback

01:46:44.370 --> 01:46:45.820
that you can give about that?

01:46:45.820 --> 01:46:49.044
I can't identify
exactly what it is.

